WEBVTT

00:02.400 --> 00:04.425
(overlapping voices on TV)

00:10.740 --> 00:12.799
Don't you ever get tired
of this memory game?

00:12.840 --> 00:15.570
You do it every morning.
The mind is a muscle, Watson.

00:15.610 --> 00:18.545
It needs to be exercised
regularly lest It turn flabby.

00:18.580 --> 00:20.639
Most people
just read a book.

00:20.680 --> 00:22.614
I am reading a book.

00:22.650 --> 00:24.641
Well, do you mind
turning it off for a minute?

00:24.690 --> 00:26.555
I want to finish our_
conversation from last night.

00:26.590 --> 00:28.148
(sighs)

00:29.630 --> 00:31.279
Okay, I meant
all of them.

00:31.330 --> 00:33.298
Absorbing and cataloguing
several pieces of information

00:33.330 --> 00:35.594
at the same time
is the whole point.

00:35.630 --> 00:37.598
Talk away.

00:37.630 --> 00:39.564
Okay, well, then I want us
to get more serious

00:39.600 --> 00:41.261
about finding a sponsor.

00:41.300 --> 00:43.768
Why do I need a sponsor
when I have a companion?

00:43.810 --> 00:45.801
Because you only have me
for a few more weeks.

00:45.840 --> 00:47.808
A sponsor is permanent,
someone who's...

00:47.840 --> 00:49.569
struggled with their
own addictions

00:49.610 --> 00:51.840
and is gonna offer you
lifelong support and advice,

00:51.880 --> 00:53.370
which is what you need.

00:54.820 --> 00:57.482
The drugs that I took
seemed to light up my brain.

00:57.520 --> 00:59.351
Suddenly I realized

00:59.390 --> 01:02.382
the power I held,
the power to rule,

01:02.430 --> 01:04.751
to make the world grovel
at my feet.

01:06.660 --> 01:08.423
(video rewinding)

01:08.460 --> 01:11.429
The drugs I took seemed
to light up my brain.

01:11.470 --> 01:14.689
Suddenly I realized
the power I held,

01:14.740 --> 01:16.207
the power to rule,

01:16.240 --> 01:18.868
to make the world grovel
at my feet.

01:18.910 --> 01:20.707
Okay.

01:20.740 --> 01:22.674
Well, I know someone
who might be a good fit for you.

01:22.710 --> 01:24.200
I've worked with him before.

01:24.250 --> 01:25.603
Let's have coffee
with him, okay?

01:25.650 --> 01:28.539
IfI needed a sponsor,
that would sound delightful.

01:28.580 --> 01:31.447
I don't. Just like I didn't
need a sober companion.

01:31.490 --> 01:32.787
And you didn't need rehab

01:32.820 --> 01:34.310
and you didn't
need drug counseling

01:34.360 --> 01:35.759
and you didn't need
any help of any kind.

01:35.790 --> 01:38.156
I know.

01:38.190 --> 01:40.192
It's just coffee.

01:41.300 --> 01:42.722
Sherlock.
Fine. I'll go.

01:42.770 --> 01:44.795
Provided I can get some peace
and quiet around here.

01:48.670 --> 01:51.639
(overlapping voices)

01:51.670 --> 01:53.809
MAN:
We completely
understand, Mr. McKeon.

01:53.840 --> 01:54.875
Fluid layout.

01:54.910 --> 01:56.741
No, we-we agree, uh...

01:56.780 --> 01:59.715
grid-based design, it's gone
the way of the dinosaur.

01:59.750 --> 02:02.389
Will do.

02:02.420 --> 02:04.638
All right. Take care.

02:04.690 --> 02:07.488
_Our favorite _client's
still wringing his hands?

02:07.520 --> 02:09.158
Guy just does not get
Web design.

02:09.190 --> 02:12.193
'Course, he's like 45
or something.

02:13.560 --> 02:15.551
(beeping)

02:18.730 --> 02:20.436
(beeping continues)
No.

02:23.770 --> 02:26.307
I think it's coming
from inside the vent.

02:31.480 --> 02:33.175
(beeping continues)

02:33.220 --> 02:35.711
Yeah, repair guy must have
dropped his phone or something.

02:35.750 --> 02:37.843
MAN: That's going
to make us crazy.

02:37.890 --> 02:39.881
MAN 2:
I'll call maintenance.

02:46.730 --> 02:49.790
(beeping continues)

03:19.030 --> 03:21.851
The blast detonated in
the southeast corner

03:21.900 --> 03:24.368
of the office around
9:15 this morning.

03:24.400 --> 03:26.539
Killed two people,

03:26.570 --> 03:28.765
Dave Preston and Royce Maltz,

03:28.800 --> 03:30.904
and injured 11 more.

03:30.940 --> 03:32.805
Chemical composition
of the device?

03:32.840 --> 03:35.001
The bomb squad's
working on it.

03:35.040 --> 03:36.576
All they know
for sure is that

03:36.610 --> 03:37.941
the bomb was stashed
in that air vent.

03:37.980 --> 03:40.847
Both of the victims were
employees of this company?

03:40.880 --> 03:42.381
BELL:
Parabolic Web Industries.

03:42.420 --> 03:45.412
They design and maintain
corporate Web sites.

03:45.450 --> 03:47.384
We're looking
into whether anybody had beef

03:47.420 --> 03:49.559
with the firm.

03:49.590 --> 03:51.751
OFFICER:
Captain?

04:07.910 --> 04:10.879
I imagine you won't miss this
when you're gone.

04:12.450 --> 04:14.918
In a few weeks,
you'll be with your new client.

04:14.950 --> 04:18.044
No more crime scenes,
no more death and destruction.

04:18.090 --> 04:21.514
Most dangerous place you'll go
is a support group meeting

04:21.560 --> 04:23.858
where they've run out of coffee.

04:23.890 --> 04:26.825
Firstly, I don't have
a next client, and secondly,

04:26.860 --> 04:29.397
you're right, I'm not gonna
miss seeing this stuff.

04:40.580 --> 04:43.071
You see this?

04:43.110 --> 04:44.441
That's packing paper.

04:44.480 --> 04:46.539
It's used to fill the gap

04:46.580 --> 04:48.844
between the fuel and the
blast cap on a pipe bomb.

04:48.880 --> 04:50.848
When the bomb detonates,

04:50.890 --> 04:52.619
this paper is ejected
through the barrel

04:52.660 --> 04:54.548
before it has time
to fully combust.

04:54.590 --> 04:57.627
Now, weapons-grade munitions
uses pulp filler,

04:57.660 --> 04:59.855
not newspaper.

04:59.900 --> 05:01.549
The bomb squad
said the same thing.

05:01.600 --> 05:02.919
We're already
running a check

05:02.970 --> 05:04.460
on _recent _
commerCIal burglaries

05:04.500 --> 05:06.866
to see if _
anyone's missmg

05:06.900 --> 05:11.030
any flammable chemicals
or gunpowder.

05:11.070 --> 05:13.004
You got something?

05:13.040 --> 05:15.008
Motherboard.

05:15.040 --> 05:17.042
BELL:
You know this is
a computer company, right?

05:17.080 --> 05:18.877
Well, that's just it, Detective.

05:18.910 --> 05:20.741
This is not from a computer.

05:20.780 --> 05:21.940
It's from a pager.

05:21.980 --> 05:23.880
Note the presence of a receiver

05:23.920 --> 05:25.808
but the absence
of a transmitter.

05:27.060 --> 05:28.948
What's it doing here?

05:28.990 --> 05:31.481
Pre-explosion, this place looked
like the deck of a starship.

05:31.530 --> 05:33.054
It's unlikely any of
the firm's employees

05:33.100 --> 05:36.467
would use technology
as antiquated as a pager.

05:36.500 --> 05:38.127
You're saying
it's part of the bomb?

05:38.170 --> 05:40.968
I'm saying this may be
the bomb's detonator.

05:41.000 --> 05:42.900
The good news is, if it's
not too badly damaged,

05:42.940 --> 05:45.408
you'll be able to trace
the account.

05:45.440 --> 05:48.477
I'll get this
to tech assist right away.

05:48.510 --> 05:50.978
I'll let you know
when we hear something.

05:51.010 --> 05:53.012
If the motherboard
is still functional, how long

05:53.050 --> 05:54.972
do you think it's gonna take
the police to get a number?

05:55.020 --> 05:57.011
Two, maybe three hours. Why?

05:59.050 --> 06:00.608
WATSON:
The sponsor's name is Adrian,

06:00.660 --> 06:02.719
and he works on the floor
of the stock exchange.

06:02.760 --> 06:03.920
Good thinking, Watson.

06:03.960 --> 06:05.518
You know how much
I enjoy bankers.

06:05.560 --> 06:06.754
Glad to _see _
you've been paying attention

06:06.800 --> 06:08.051
over the last few weeks.

06:08.100 --> 06:10.489
Actually, he's an officer
with the SEC.

06:10.530 --> 06:12.896
So he spends his days
keeping bankers in line.

06:12.940 --> 06:15.898
He also spent four years at
the London School of Economics,

06:15.940 --> 06:18.158
so he knows
your old stomping grounds.

06:18.210 --> 06:20.735
You think I'd just pick any name
out of a hat? Oh, there he is.

06:20.780 --> 06:22.668
Hey, Adrian.

06:22.710 --> 06:25.543
Hi. Adrian, Sherlock.

06:25.580 --> 06:27.116
Pleasure.

06:29.620 --> 06:31.918
Well, you guys talk.

06:31.950 --> 06:33.986
I'll be over there
when you're ready.

06:37.960 --> 06:39.689
A hypothetical, Adrian.

06:39.730 --> 06:41.152
I call you in the middle
of the night,

06:41.200 --> 06:42.724
I tell you that I'm thinking
of using again,

06:42.770 --> 06:43.998
and that if I don't,
I might die.

06:44.030 --> 06:45.463
How do you respond?

06:45.500 --> 06:47.036
Well, Sherlock,
I think I'd start

06:47.070 --> 06:49.630
by reminding you, you got
to take it one day at a time,

06:49.670 --> 06:51.160
and that every clean
day is a victory.

06:51.210 --> 06:53.633
I call you and tell you
that an enemy has poisoned me

06:53.680 --> 06:55.079
with a powerful
neuroleptic agent.

06:55.110 --> 06:57.203
The only antidote is a
healthy dose of diphenhydramine,

06:57.250 --> 06:58.706
of which I have plenty.

06:58.750 --> 07:00.047
Do you advise me to take it?

07:00.080 --> 07:01.547
Diphen...

07:01.580 --> 07:02.911
Diphenhydramine.

07:04.190 --> 07:05.714
You find
murder-by-poisoning humorous?

07:05.750 --> 07:07.149
No, of course not. I just...

07:07.190 --> 07:09.112
The diphenhydramine,
Adrian, do I take it?

07:09.160 --> 07:12.721
If it's gonna save your life,

07:12.760 --> 07:14.853
then yeah, of course you do.

07:24.940 --> 07:26.999
That's your idea of a
good fit, seriously?

07:27.040 --> 07:29.508
I told you, he's one
of the best sponsors I know.

07:29.550 --> 07:31.848
Peter Platitude? I was waiting
for him to hold my hand

07:31.880 --> 07:33.472
so we could recite
the Serenity Prayer.

07:33.520 --> 07:35.738
Okay, if you want to hear
something other that platitudes,

07:35.780 --> 07:37.987
try listening to the guy
for more than two minutes.

07:38.020 --> 07:40.659
The man encouraged me to take
diphenhydramine, Watson.

07:40.690 --> 07:42.089
A deliriant.

07:42.120 --> 07:43.724
The Republic of Zambia
recently classified that

07:43.760 --> 07:45.159
a controlled substance.

07:45.190 --> 07:47.192
Now, what kind of a sponsor
would allow his sponsee

07:47.230 --> 07:49.027
to risk their sobriety
over a simple case

07:49.060 --> 07:50.027
of neuroleptic poisoning?

07:50.070 --> 07:51.594
Okay, you think I don't know

07:51.630 --> 07:53.063
there's no right answer
to that question?

07:53.100 --> 07:54.738
You don't want Adrian?

07:54.770 --> 07:55.998
Okay. This is a process.

07:56.040 --> 07:58.065
We can look for other candidates
at group tonight.

07:58.110 --> 07:59.998
But know this: We are gonna
find you a sponsor

08:00.040 --> 08:02.076
before my stint is up, okay?

08:02.110 --> 08:05.602
(phone ringing)

08:05.650 --> 08:07.015
Ha.

08:07.050 --> 08:08.074
Captain.

08:08.120 --> 08:09.610
That motherboard you found--

08:09.650 --> 08:11.140
bomb squad confirmed
it was part of the device,

08:11.190 --> 08:12.782
so touch.

08:12.820 --> 08:14.219
The pager it was part of
was prepaid,

08:14.260 --> 08:15.989
so there was no subscriber info,

08:16.020 --> 08:18.079
but luckily, the tech assist

08:18.130 --> 08:19.825
was able to pull
a number off it.

08:19.860 --> 08:22.090
And the same phone
called the pager

08:22.130 --> 08:23.688
three times this morning,

08:23.730 --> 08:26.665
and each call was within seconds
of the bomb going off.

08:26.700 --> 08:28.292
Were you able
to trace the number?

08:28.340 --> 08:32.003
Yeah, to a plumber
named Rennie Jacobs from Queens.

08:32.040 --> 08:34.235
And get this,
he just did a six-year stretch

08:34.280 --> 08:35.599
for burning down his apartment

08:35.640 --> 08:37.779
in an insurance fraud scheme.

08:37.810 --> 08:39.175
Any particular reason

08:39.210 --> 08:41.110
he'd want to depredate
that Web design firm?

08:41.150 --> 08:43.880
No clue, but, uh,
if you want to see him

08:43.920 --> 08:46.218
live and in person,
he just got here.

08:46.250 --> 08:47.649
I was just trying
to call in

08:47.690 --> 08:49.555
a breakfast sandwich order,
thatsit

08:49.590 --> 08:51.729
Three times you called
that pager, Mr. Jacobs.

08:51.760 --> 08:53.125
Three times.

08:53.160 --> 08:55.628
You said the pager number
was 555-0164, right?

08:55.660 --> 08:57.025
212 area code?

08:57.070 --> 09:00.096
I was trying to call
Miracle Deli on 113th.

09:00.140 --> 09:01.698
Their number is off

09:01.740 --> 09:05.107
by one digit. 0165.

09:05.140 --> 09:08.177
I must've misdialed, 'cause
when they didn't answer,
(line ringing)

09:08.210 --> 09:09.905
I hit redial.

09:09.950 --> 09:11.076
Twice.

09:11.110 --> 09:12.975
MAN: Miracle Deli.
Pickup or delivery?

09:13.020 --> 09:14.874
He's telling the truth

09:14.920 --> 09:16.740
about the numbers being off
by a single digit.

09:16.790 --> 09:18.189
Yeah, we know.

09:18.220 --> 09:20.984
Coincidence bugs me, but not
enough to cut him loose.

09:21.020 --> 09:22.726
(phone vibrates)

09:22.760 --> 09:24.284
I got to step out.

09:24.330 --> 09:26.127
Bomb squad wants to brief me.

09:27.230 --> 09:30.267
(door opens, closes)

09:30.300 --> 09:33.167
You don't look convinced.

09:33.200 --> 09:35.760
Bomb-building
is a dangerous venture.

09:35.800 --> 09:37.768
It requires patience,
precision,

09:37.810 --> 09:39.835
attention to detail.

09:39.880 --> 09:42.178
Mr. J_acobs_' wristwatch
is nine minutes slow

09:42.210 --> 09:44.178
and his fly
is three-quarters down.

09:44.210 --> 09:47.373
That doesn't scream
detail-oriented.

09:47.420 --> 09:50.241
Ted Kaczynski looked like
a hobo puked another hobo.

09:50.290 --> 09:52.246
He managed
to hurt plenty of people.

09:53.790 --> 09:55.781
Point taken.

09:59.030 --> 10:00.895
Yeah.

10:02.730 --> 10:04.129
Can I help you?

10:04.170 --> 10:06.195
This is the, uh...

10:06.230 --> 10:08.130
the bomb's power source,
I presume?

10:08.170 --> 10:09.933
Six volt.

10:09.970 --> 10:12.029
Very interesting company,
PrimSource Battery.

10:12.070 --> 10:14.106
Founded in 1888
by British expat

10:14.140 --> 10:15.676
and purveyor
of mechanical novelties,

10:15.710 --> 10:17.268
Hubert Primler.

10:17.310 --> 10:20.177
They switched to making
batteries full-time in 1907,

10:20.220 --> 10:22.142
each one stamped
with the company's

10:22.180 --> 10:24.410
now iconic rising-sun logo.

10:24.450 --> 10:26.714
The logo remained unchanged
until 2008,

10:26.760 --> 10:28.648
when a small oak tree was added

10:28.690 --> 10:30.351
to commemorate
the company's centenary.

10:30.390 --> 10:32.995
Yet this one has no oak tree.

10:34.060 --> 10:35.197
That means that battery

10:35.230 --> 10:37.061
is more than four years old.

10:37.100 --> 10:40.194
Odd, isn't it,
go to all that trouble

10:40.240 --> 10:41.434
building an elaborate
explosive device

10:41.470 --> 10:43.199
and then power it with an old

10:43.240 --> 10:44.730
and potentially
unreliable battery?

10:44.770 --> 10:46.977
Odd, yes,
but not impossible.

10:47.010 --> 10:49.308
Holmes, Holmes,
I've only got a few minutes here

10:49.340 --> 10:51.205
to pick Bennett's brain
before I have

10:51.250 --> 10:52.444
to stand in front
of 20 cameras

10:52.480 --> 10:53.811
to explain what happened
this morning.

10:53.850 --> 10:55.875
What about that?
What about what?

10:55.920 --> 10:57.717
OFFICER:
It's the president.

10:57.750 --> 10:59.911
Wrong. It's the senator.
Captain...

10:59.960 --> 11:01.279
Senator Obama,
not President Obama.

11:01.320 --> 11:03.823
You can tell from the lack
of gray in his hair.

11:03.860 --> 11:06.124
He's right. I can make
out a date on this one.

11:06.160 --> 11:08.151
October 13, 2008.

11:08.200 --> 11:09.451
So, what are you saying?

11:09.500 --> 11:11.229
That battery is four years old.

11:11.270 --> 11:13.431
These shreds of newspaper
are four years old.

11:13.470 --> 11:16.098
The bomb that exploded
this morning was four years old.

11:16.140 --> 11:17.300
But why would the suspect
build a bomb

11:17.340 --> 11:18.932
and sit on it for four years?

11:18.970 --> 11:20.801
He wouldn't have.

11:20.840 --> 11:22.330
And in Rennie Jacobs's case,
he couldn't have.

11:22.380 --> 11:23.779
He was in prison
four years ago.

11:23.810 --> 11:25.243
I think he was telling the truth

11:25.280 --> 11:27.214
when he said he dialed
the wrong number this morning.

11:27.250 --> 11:30.742
We have the man who set it off
accidentally in 2012.

11:30.790 --> 11:34.453
Now we just need the man who
intended to set it off in 2008.

11:38.830 --> 11:40.923
You're sure he's not the
one who built the bomb?
Sure? No.

11:42.530 --> 11:45.090
The NYPD can continue
to poke and prod him.

11:45.130 --> 11:47.189
In the meantime,
you and I can push forward

11:47.240 --> 11:49.128
on this, our new front.

11:49.170 --> 11:52.037
It is a lovely front.

11:52.070 --> 11:53.970
Hmm. Vanowen _
Strategic Communications.

11:54.010 --> 11:57.002
Public relations consultancy
founded in 1994

11:57.050 --> 12:00.372
by Harrington School of Business
alumna Heather Vanowen.

12:00.420 --> 12:03.014
The firm is particularly adept
at solving image crises

12:03.050 --> 12:04.779
of the corporate variety,

12:04.820 --> 12:08.187
making them one-stop shopping
for many of the Fortune 500.

12:08.220 --> 12:11.849
Spin doctors
of the highest order, and

12:11.890 --> 12:14.029
former tenants
of the midtown offices

12:14.060 --> 12:16.324
ravaged by a homemade bomb
this morning.

12:16.360 --> 12:19.124
They occupied the space
until December 2008.

12:19.170 --> 12:22.094
Now, if I'm right and the bomb
was planted that October,

12:22.140 --> 12:24.267
this company
or one of its employees

12:24.310 --> 12:26.505
may have been
the intended target.

12:26.540 --> 12:29.270
WOMAN:
Mr. Holmes?

12:29.310 --> 12:30.504
Heather Vanowen.

12:30.550 --> 12:32.370
This is Earl Wheeler, my CFO.

12:32.410 --> 12:35.516
We were told you work
with the police.

12:35.550 --> 12:37.211
I'm their consultant.

12:37.250 --> 12:38.410
This is Miss Watson.

12:38.450 --> 12:40.884
She is my consultant,
slash housekeep.

12:40.920 --> 12:42.285
So, how can we
help you today?

12:42.320 --> 12:44.254
Well, you can start
by telling us

12:44.290 --> 12:47.293
who maybe have wanted
to blow you up in 2008.

12:48.830 --> 12:50.388
I'm stunned.

12:50.430 --> 12:52.159
I-I saw the story
on the news this morning.

12:52.200 --> 12:54.532
I knew that was our old
office space, but...

12:54.570 --> 12:56.902
I never would have guessed
that that bomb

12:56.940 --> 12:58.965
was meant for us.
WHEELER:
So you honestly think

12:59.010 --> 13:01.228
it was just sitting
there this whole time?

13:01.280 --> 13:03.339
The police think it was tucked
into an air vent.

13:03.380 --> 13:05.245
If that part of the building's
climate control system

13:05.280 --> 13:07.043
had never needed repair--

13:07.080 --> 13:09.310
and judging by this morning's
events, it didn't--

13:09.350 --> 13:11.318
it could have gone
undiscovered indefinitely.

13:11.350 --> 13:13.511
Okay, but why this morning?

13:13.560 --> 13:15.448
Why'd it go off
after all this time?

13:15.490 --> 13:17.151
The bomb was detonated
by a pager.

13:17.190 --> 13:20.921
In 2008, the company
that made that pager

13:20.960 --> 13:25.021
had no signal towers within
42 blocks of your old offices.

13:25.070 --> 13:26.469
In 2010,

13:26.500 --> 13:29.264
they erected a new tower

13:29.300 --> 13:31.200
a mere three blocks away.

13:31.240 --> 13:33.003
So the bomb didn't detonate

13:33.040 --> 13:35.338
in 2008 because the call
couldn't go through.

13:35.380 --> 13:37.905
The question is:
Who built the device,

13:37.950 --> 13:40.510
and what may they have had
against your company?

13:40.550 --> 13:42.279
I'm sure that we've made
our fair share of enemies

13:42.320 --> 13:44.345
along the way, but, um...
someone who would build

13:44.390 --> 13:45.584
a bomb?

13:45.620 --> 13:48.088
The ELM.

13:48.120 --> 13:50.520
The Earth Liberty Militia.

13:50.560 --> 13:52.255
We got some threatening letters
from them in 2008.

13:52.290 --> 13:54.429
They're an ecoterrorist
group, right?

13:54.460 --> 13:56.428
They've bombed a few other
companies over the years.

13:56.460 --> 13:59.293
What would an ecoterrorist group
have against a PR firm?

13:59.330 --> 14:01.469
Our clients.

14:01.500 --> 14:03.968
We work with some of
the major energy conglomerates.

14:04.010 --> 14:05.363
Occasionally we
have to help them

14:05.410 --> 14:06.638
_ smooth over_their
image after mishaps.

14:06.670 --> 14:09.104
200 million gallons of oil

14:09.140 --> 14:11.108
