15:08.970 --> 15:11.109
Seriously, can you just
examine those at home?

15:11.140 --> 15:12.562
We have work
to do here.

15:12.610 --> 15:14.999
Oh, yeah.
Sponsor Search 2012.

15:15.040 --> 15:17.076
I have to say, Watson,

15:17.110 --> 15:19.305
it's a bit of _
a motley crew tonight.

15:19.350 --> 15:21.443
I don't think these are
my kind of addicts.

15:21.480 --> 15:24.517
I think this is going to be
a much longer

15:24.550 --> 15:26.438
and more involved process
than we initially thought.

15:26.490 --> 15:28.708
You have 23 days.

15:28.760 --> 15:30.489
Then our time is up.

15:33.130 --> 15:34.950
MAN:
My name is Alfredo,
and I'm an addict.

15:35.000 --> 15:36.490
ALL:
Hi, Alfredo.

15:36.530 --> 15:40.091
ALFREDO:
Started boosting cars
when I was 14.

15:40.140 --> 15:41.459
By the time I turned 18,

15:41.500 --> 15:43.604
I was the best there is.

15:43.640 --> 15:45.505
Ain't a car in the city
I can't steal.

15:45.540 --> 15:47.303
Him.

15:47.340 --> 15:48.534
Hmm?
Now I'm flush
with cash,

15:48.580 --> 15:50.571
I'm bored... I turn to drugs.

15:50.610 --> 15:53.647
I want him to
be my sponsor.

15:53.680 --> 15:55.170
Took my first hit at 19...

15:57.650 --> 16:01.017
This phrase,
"on your beam ends,"

16:01.060 --> 16:03.585
it appears in five
of the seven threats.

16:03.630 --> 16:05.689
I'm certain I've heard
it before; I just...

16:05.730 --> 16:07.357
can't recall where.

16:07.400 --> 16:08.594
"On your beam ends."

16:08.630 --> 16:10.268
A nautical idiom
first documented

16:10.300 --> 16:12.621
in Captain Frederick
Marryat's 1830 novel

16:12.670 --> 16:14.365
The King's Own,

16:14.400 --> 16:16.265
signifying a situation
of great peril.

16:16.300 --> 16:18.302
Strange for such
an aberrant phrase

16:18.340 --> 16:19.534
to appear so repeatedly.

16:19.570 --> 16:22.778
Are you seriously
going to make me ask?

16:22.810 --> 16:25.142
Ask what?
About your sponsor, Alfredo.

16:25.180 --> 16:26.670
Delightful fellow.

16:26.710 --> 16:28.314
He's agreed to meet us
both tomorrow for coffee.

16:28.350 --> 16:30.284
So we can get to
know one another.

16:30.320 --> 16:31.685
You don't approve?

16:31.720 --> 16:33.585
I'm just a little confused,
that's all.

16:33.620 --> 16:35.315
I mean, you actually met Adrian.

16:35.360 --> 16:36.679
You talked to him
before you turned him down.

16:36.720 --> 16:39.621
You heard Alfredo speak
for 15 seconds.

16:39.660 --> 16:41.457
Oh, have you not
figured out by now

16:41.500 --> 16:44.219
that I see far more_
than your average addict?

16:44.270 --> 16:45.760
My observational skills
are second to none.

16:45.800 --> 16:48.530
I know. I know that.
I just... I want to leave you

16:48.570 --> 16:51.061
in the best situation possible.
It's important to me.

16:51.110 --> 16:52.805
Got it.
Good. I'm glad.

16:52.840 --> 16:54.603
No. "On your beam ends."

16:54.640 --> 16:56.107
I've got it.

16:56.140 --> 16:58.677
I know where I was
when I heard it.

17:03.090 --> 17:04.409
That one.

17:04.450 --> 17:06.611
That's where I saw it,
weeks ago.

17:06.650 --> 17:09.210
But what was the context?

17:12.660 --> 17:14.252
Yellow cartoon sponge man,

17:14.300 --> 17:17.098
sports news,
mouthwash advert,

17:17.130 --> 17:19.166
Arctic Blue...
You want to tell me
what you're domg?

17:19.200 --> 17:21.498
Uh, method of loci,
mnemonic device.

17:21.540 --> 17:24.202
Relies on memorized spatial
relationships to establish,

17:24.240 --> 17:27.676
catalogue and recollect
memorial content.

17:29.240 --> 17:31.071
If I remember what was
on these SIX screens,

17:31.110 --> 17:33.772
I'll remember what
was on the seventh.

17:36.680 --> 17:39.683
Fat lady, new cookbook,
insufferable.

17:39.720 --> 17:41.654
Erectile dysfunction.
Nature program, penguins.

17:41.690 --> 17:44.625
And... talk show.

17:44.660 --> 17:47.754
The topic was...
international whaling laws.

17:47.800 --> 17:51.395
Two guests got into an argument.

17:58.640 --> 18:00.733
MAN: _
You are not seriously suggesting

18:00.780 --> 18:03.305
that cleaning out the
Pacific Ocean is a good idea.

18:03.350 --> 18:04.669
What do you suggest
we tell the Japanese worker

18:04.710 --> 18:06.177
whose livelihood
depends upon this trade?

18:06.210 --> 18:08.314
MAN:
Just... you don't get it.

18:08.350 --> 18:11.183
One day 50 years from now,
when you're on your beam ends,

18:11.220 --> 18:13.609
you'll wish you'd done
more when you could have.

18:13.660 --> 18:16.117
That's the same bombast

18:16.160 --> 18:17.525
I read in the ELM letters.

18:17.560 --> 18:18.652
It's the same hyperbole.

18:18.690 --> 18:20.123
Same weird phrase.

18:20.160 --> 18:21.650
You really think it's him?

18:21.700 --> 18:23.565
I know a way to find out.

18:23.600 --> 18:25.397
MAN:
I'm confused, Detective.

18:25.430 --> 18:28.763
You're accusing me of being
some sort of ecoterrorist?

18:28.800 --> 18:31.200
One of our special consultants

18:31.240 --> 18:34.209
thinks your speech pattern
is a match for these letters.

18:34.240 --> 18:35.776
For the last time,

18:35.810 --> 18:37.846
I have never seen
these letters before.

18:37.880 --> 18:40.348
I don't know anything
about the ELM,

18:40.380 --> 18:42.314
and I certainly didn't
build any bombs.

18:42.350 --> 18:45.547
Lie, lie and lie.

18:45.590 --> 18:46.887
Who the hell are you?

18:46.920 --> 18:49.218
I am the man with the button.

18:49.260 --> 18:51.148
It's from the elevator
down the hall.

18:51.190 --> 18:52.851
You pushed it
to get to this floor.

18:52.890 --> 18:54.790
As soon as you disembarked,
I removed it,

18:54.830 --> 18:57.321
and took it to the department's
latent print unit.

18:57.370 --> 18:59.520
It has your fingerprint
on it, you see.

18:59.570 --> 19:01.697
Which means it has
a great deal in common

19:01.740 --> 19:04.868
with a component
from a bomb the ELM detonated

19:04.910 --> 19:08.334
in a lumber mill
in Utica in 2005.

19:08.380 --> 19:11.269
Button... bomb.

19:11.310 --> 19:13.744
Button...
bomb.

19:13.780 --> 19:16.317
The similarities are quite
striking, wouldn't you agree?

19:16.350 --> 19:17.908
You built the ELM bombs,
Mr. Knowles.

19:17.950 --> 19:19.747
And you wrote
those letters.

19:19.790 --> 19:21.678
It's too bad you didn't
go back for the one

19:21.720 --> 19:23.881
you left at Vanowen S.C. when
you realized it was defective.

19:23.930 --> 19:26.353
Maybe you wouldn't be facing
two murder charges today.

19:28.630 --> 19:30.518
I bombed that lumber mill.

19:32.500 --> 19:35.367
And I wrote these letters
to Vanowen S.C.

19:35.400 --> 19:37.664
But you know what I didn't do?

19:37.710 --> 19:38.904
Follow up on them.

19:38.940 --> 19:42.637
By 2008, I had
successfully detonated

19:42.680 --> 19:45.706
nitrate-based bombs at
five different companies.

19:45.750 --> 19:49.277
I was established,
and I was taken very seriously.

19:49.320 --> 19:52.517
Vanowen S.C. was one of
several dozen busmesses

19:52.550 --> 19:54.609
I threatened but never bombed.

19:54.660 --> 19:56.855
Why am I not surprised
you'd take credit

19:56.890 --> 19:58.778
for every bombing except

19:58.830 --> 20:01.856
the one that
killed two people?

20:01.900 --> 20:03.697
(small explosion)
WATSON:
Was that you?

20:03.730 --> 20:05.368
Was what me?

20:08.600 --> 20:11.307
What did those balls
ever do to you?

20:11.340 --> 20:12.864
(breathing deeply)

20:12.910 --> 20:14.935
They're dying
for a good cause, Watson.

20:14.980 --> 20:17.574
Of course they are.
Ah!

20:19.450 --> 20:20.678
Did you know

20:20.720 --> 20:22.517
that when a bomb explodes,

20:22.550 --> 20:24.939
the component that houses
the fuel is often atomized?

20:24.990 --> 20:27.811
Now, this can make it difficult,
if not downright impossible,

20:27.860 --> 20:30.852
to identify the device's
chemical composition.

20:30.890 --> 20:33.256
The NYPD bomb squad
is currently struggling

20:33.300 --> 20:35.495
with this very conundrum,
so I thought I would help.

20:35.530 --> 20:37.896
With tennis balls?_
I'm attempting to replicate

20:37.930 --> 20:40.694
the odor and burn pattern
of the office bombing

20:40.740 --> 20:42.799
using a few of my own
concoctions, and these balls

20:42.840 --> 20:45.400
make the perfect
delivery mechanism.

20:54.880 --> 20:55.869
(breathing deeply)

20:55.920 --> 20:57.808
(sniffing)

20:57.850 --> 20:59.511
When Edgar Knowles was
arrested this afternoon,

20:59.550 --> 21:00.949
he confessed to setting off

21:00.990 --> 21:04.448
five nitrate-based bombs
at various busmesses.

21:04.490 --> 21:06.424
No self-respecting eco-warrior

21:06.460 --> 21:09.520
would use toxic, man-made
chemicals in his bombs.

21:09.560 --> 21:12.358
He would use
natural ingredients.

21:12.400 --> 21:14.595
Smells like fertilizer.

21:14.640 --> 21:15.834
With good reason.

21:15.870 --> 21:17.838
Beyond its horticultural
employments,

21:17.870 --> 21:19.360
fertilizer can be
distilled down

21:19.410 --> 21:22.538
and mixed into a rather potent
nitrate accelerant.

21:22.580 --> 21:24.673
This ball is filled
with the stuff.

21:24.710 --> 21:27.838
If Knowles did try
to blow up Vanowen S.C.,

21:27.880 --> 21:30.019
he would have used nitrates,
and if he'd used nitrates,

21:30.050 --> 21:31.984
the bomb would have filled
the air with an odor

21:32.020 --> 21:33.988
as pungent
as it is distinctive,

21:34.020 --> 21:35.988
the same odor that
you're smelling right now.

21:36.020 --> 21:37.521
The thing is,
I didn't smell

21:37.560 --> 21:38.982
any fertilizer
when we were there.

21:39.030 --> 21:40.850
I smelled something else.

21:40.900 --> 21:42.959
It was foreign to me
in the moment, but...

21:43.000 --> 21:44.695
I have managed to recreate it
with the help of

21:44.730 --> 21:46.789
my little
round friends here.

21:46.830 --> 21:48.695
I am now certain
that the bomb was made

21:48.740 --> 21:49.934
using potassium chlorate.

21:49.970 --> 21:51.528
It's an accelerant made of

21:51.570 --> 21:53.572
gasoline, bleach
and petroleum jelly.

21:53.610 --> 21:55.999
Are you saying that Edgar
Knowles was telling the truth

21:56.040 --> 21:57.871
when he told you that
he didn't build the bomb

21:57.910 --> 21:59.741
that exploded at Vanowen S.C.?

21:59.780 --> 22:03.011
I am.
Well, if he didn't
build it, who did?

22:03.050 --> 22:05.917
Haven't the foggiest.

22:10.630 --> 22:13.622
(indistinct chatter,
phone ringing)

22:25.810 --> 22:26.765
(raps on fence)
Hey.

22:26.810 --> 22:29.699
Heard you were
looking for me?

22:29.740 --> 22:32.709
Yesterday, you gave
us Edgar Knowles
on a silver platter.

22:32.750 --> 22:34.741
Now you're telling me

22:34.780 --> 22:37.146
he did every bomb
except for the one

22:37.180 --> 22:38.943
from two days ago?
As I said before,

22:38.990 --> 22:41.515
that bomb was built using
potassium chlorate.

22:41.560 --> 22:43.824
Yeah, and Knowles only used
ones with cow manure.

22:43.860 --> 22:45.157
I heard you.
That's not enough.

22:45.190 --> 22:47.124
There's _more. _
I came in this morning

22:47.160 --> 22:49.628
to reexamine the
bomb's components,
and I pieced together

22:49.660 --> 22:50.991
some of the strips
of packing paper

22:51.030 --> 22:52.759
that were used.
I managed to form

22:52.800 --> 22:54.836
almost a third of a page
of the October 13 edition

22:54.870 --> 22:56.428
of the New York Times.

22:56.470 --> 22:58.529
This particular clump
caught my eye.

22:58.570 --> 23:01.630
I saw small, almost
imperceptible indentations

23:01.680 --> 23:03.648
along the upper fringe.

23:03.680 --> 23:04.772
I don't see anything.

23:04.810 --> 23:06.744
You wouldn't.

23:06.780 --> 23:08.748
Well, most people
wouldn't, which is why

23:08.780 --> 23:11.010
I traced over it.

23:12.790 --> 23:14.155
The paper
that was used

23:14.190 --> 23:16.055
in the bomb was
beneath another piece

23:16.090 --> 23:17.921
of paper when
someone wrote that word.

23:17.960 --> 23:19.689
They pressed hard enough
to make indentations.

23:19.730 --> 23:20.856
Now, I already checked it

23:20.900 --> 23:22.094
against Edgar Knowles's
handwriting.

23:22.130 --> 23:23.097
It's not a match.

23:23.130 --> 23:24.199
All due respect,
Holmes.

23:24.230 --> 23:25.424
So what?

23:25.470 --> 23:26.926
Maybe he had help with the bomb.

23:26.970 --> 23:28.164
Maybe that person wrote some

23:28.200 --> 23:29.997
weird note on top
of the newspaper.

23:30.040 --> 23:32.531
As I said previously, I believe
Edgar Knowles worked alone.

23:32.570 --> 23:34.572
And as I said previously,
I still like him

23:34.610 --> 23:36.874
for the last bomb.

23:36.910 --> 23:39.208
The threats against Vanowen
S.C. were never made public,

23:39.250 --> 23:40.808
which means, aside
from the police,

23:40.850 --> 23:42.078
the firm's employees
were the only ones

23:42.120 --> 23:43.644
who were aware of them.

23:43.690 --> 23:44.918
I'd like you to
request a subpoena

23:44.950 --> 23:46.542
of their personnel files

23:46.590 --> 23:48.581
so that I can
reVIew them.
For what?

23:48.620 --> 23:50.451
Well, imagine you were a
disgruntled employee, hmm?

23:50.490 --> 23:52.958
You want to strike out at the
company, but you don't want

23:52.990 --> 23:55.220
to get caught, so why not take
advantage of the ELM threats

23:55.260 --> 23:56.955
to plant a device
of your own, hmm?

23:57.000 --> 23:58.729
You get the blast,
they get the blame.

23:58.770 --> 23:59.725
No.

23:59.770 --> 24:00.737
No?

24:00.770 --> 24:01.896
No subpoena.

24:01.940 --> 24:03.931
If you really want
to go poking around

24:03.970 --> 24:05.631
at Vanowen S.C.,
you're gonna have

24:05.670 --> 24:06.967
to take it up with them.

24:07.010 --> 24:08.204
(door opens)

24:08.240 --> 24:10.071
Sorry I'm late.
(door closes)

24:14.920 --> 24:17.741
I'm sure he's gonna
be here any second.

24:20.520 --> 24:22.852
I really like those...

24:22.890 --> 24:24.585
tattoos .

24:27.030 --> 24:29.590
You know, I'm just gonna text
him again and see where he is.

24:34.240 --> 24:35.992
(phone beeps)

24:39.210 --> 24:41.974
I'm really sorry, Alfredo,
but it doesn't look

24:42.010 --> 24:44.604
like Sherlock is coming
and joining us today.

24:44.650 --> 24:45.969
Be patient.

24:46.010 --> 24:48.843
First rule
of good sponsorship.

24:48.880 --> 24:51.087
Newcomers like him
don't always understand

24:51.120 --> 24:52.747
the scope of the work involved.

24:52.790 --> 24:54.883
They get frustrated.

24:54.920 --> 24:56.911
We need to be patient
and methodical with him.

24:56.960 --> 24:58.689
I was under the impression

24:58.730 --> 25:00.618
that you'd never been
a sponsor before.

25:00.660 --> 25:01.854
I haven't.

25:01.900 --> 25:03.197
But I have a great one.

25:03.230 --> 25:05.289
Taught me
everything he knows.

25:05.330 --> 25:09.164
Truth is, I've been wanting
to be a sponsor for a while now.

25:09.200 --> 25:11.532
People never ask.

25:11.570 --> 25:13.777
Think it's because I'm quiet.

25:13.810 --> 25:17.007
I can help your friend,
Miss Watson.

25:17.040 --> 25:20.077
He just needs
to give me the chance.

25:30.120 --> 25:32.554
Doing okay?

25:32.590 --> 25:34.091
Iam.

25:34.130 --> 25:36.997
And thank you again for allowing
me to peruse these files.

25:37.030 --> 25:39.567
Oh, it was
an easy decision to make.

25:39.600 --> 25:41.636
If you think there's
anyone here who has something

25:41.670 --> 25:44.559
against this company,
I would like to know.

25:47.140 --> 25:49.836
You're a fellow addict,
aren't you?

25:52.010 --> 25:53.648
Crosswords.

25:53.680 --> 25:55.045
_ You couldn't have
figured out those clues

25:55.080 --> 25:57.344
at my computer
the other day if you weren't.

25:57.380 --> 25:59.644
I dabble.

25:59.690 --> 26:01.988
Well, I wish I could say
I just dabbled.

26:02.020 --> 26:04.181
I used to have
my habit under control

26:04.230 --> 26:07.085
back when the papers
only issued one a day.

26:07.130 --> 26:09.052
Ever since they put
the last 50 years

26:09.100 --> 26:11.796
of their archives online,
I'm a lost cause.

26:11.830 --> 26:14.333
It's a miracle I get
any work done at all.

26:16.000 --> 26:17.729
You want sex?

26:17.770 --> 26:18.964
Excuse me?

26:19.010 --> 26:21.001
I'm not averse,
Ms. Vanowen.

26:21.040 --> 26:22.132
I'm just busy.

26:22.180 --> 26:24.842
Perhaps we could set
an appointment.

26:24.880 --> 26:26.848
You're flirting.

26:26.880 --> 26:28.245
This crossword talk.

26:28.280 --> 26:31.044
You find me attractive.

26:31.090 --> 26:34.116
The feeling is
mutual, mostly.

26:34.160 --> 26:35.912
The musculature
of your legs

26:35.960 --> 26:38.053
and your shoulders suggests
a certain elasticity I find

26:38.090 --> 26:40.752
quite tantalizing.

26:40.800 --> 26:43.018
I must warn you, however,
a relationship between us

26:43.060 --> 26:44.869
could never go
beyond the physical.

26:46.270 --> 26:47.794
No offense to you, of course.

26:47.840 --> 26:49.990
It's just... not my way.

26:50.040 --> 26:51.701
Hey.

26:51.740 --> 26:53.230
Am I interrupting?

26:53.270 --> 26:54.976
Nope.

26:55.010 --> 26:57.001
Not even a little.

27:02.750 --> 27:04.889
Sorry I missed our
engagement, Watson.

27:04.920 --> 27:06.410
As you can see,
